# Stop Order Coverage — Hard Invariant

## The Rule

**Every open stock position (long AND short, any size) must have at least one
stop, trail, or stop-limit order placed in IB at all times.**

No exceptions. A position without a stop is unprotected capital.

## Automated Enforcement

`position_integrity_check.py` (runs every weekday at 6:55 AM MT via scheduler):
- Calls `audit_stops(ib)` which compares positions to ALL open orders
- **Auto-triggers `update_atr_stops.py`** immediately if any gaps are found
- Sends Telegram alert listing every uncovered position

## Critical Implementation Detail

**ALWAYS use `reqAllOpenOrders()` to check stop coverage, NEVER `reqOpenOrders()`.**

`reqOpenOrders()` only returns orders placed by the current clientId.
Stop orders are placed by clientId 129 (update_atr_stops.py).
Checking from any other clientId will falsely show "no stops" for all positions.

```python
# CORRECT — sees orders from ALL clientIds
ib.reqAllOpenOrders()
time.sleep(1.5)
all_trades = ib.openTrades()
protected = {
    t.contract.symbol
    for t in all_trades
    if t.order.orderType.upper() in {"STP","TRAIL","TRAILLIMIT","STP LMT"}
}

# WRONG — only sees orders from this clientId
ib.reqOpenOrders()  # ← will miss stops placed by other clients
```

## When Gaps Are Found

1. `position_integrity_check.py` runs `update_atr_stops.py` automatically
2. Telegram alert fires with every uncovered symbol and notional size
3. If this fires mid-session, run `update_atr_stops.py` immediately:
   ```
   cd trading/scripts && python3 update_atr_stops.py
   ```

## Why This Happened (2026-03-24)

IB Gateway switched from paper (port 4002) to live (port 4001). Stop orders placed
on the paper account did not carry over to the live account. 23 of 39 positions
had no stop orders on the live side. The `audit_stops()` check was added specifically
to catch this class of failure.

## Two-Layer Stop Design

`audit_stops()` checks IB live orders (Layer 1) first. As of 2026-03-24 it also checks `pending_trades.json` as a fallback (Layer 2):

| Coverage | `audit_stops` Result |
|---|---|
| Layer 1 IB stop present | Protected — no violation |
| No IB stop, but `pending_trades.json` entry exists | `WARNING` — soft ATR trigger fires at next market open |
| No IB stop, no pending entry | `CRITICAL` (notional ≥ $500) or `WARNING` (small position) |

**The hard invariant here (every position should have a live IB stop) remains the target state.** Layer 2 is an acceptable interim state only between post-close and next market open — not a permanent substitute for a live IB stop order.

See `062-stop-system-architecture.mdc` for the full two-layer design and diagnosis steps.

## Stop Order Types Recognized

`STP`, `TRAIL`, `TRAILLIMIT`, `STP LMT`, `STOP`, `STOP LIMIT`

## Executor Responsibility

Every executor that places a stock order must ensure a stop exists post-fill.
The `atr_stops.py` module is called after every fill in the base executor.
If `update_atr_stops.py` fails to connect, it must log an error — never silently skip.
